Shm & Wal in database ops

Here's what each file represents:

XXX.db-wal (Write-Ahead Log file):
This file acts as a transaction log. Instead of writing changes directly to 
the main XXX.db database file, SQLite first appends them to the WAL file.
This allows for concurrent reads and writes, as readers can access the main 
database while writers are appending to the WAL file.
It also improves transaction performance and provides better data integrity 
in case of crashes.

Changes from the WAL file are periodically checkpointed (written) to the main 
database file.

XXX.db-shm (Shared Memory file):
This is a shared memory file used in conjunction with the WAL file.
It contains temporary data, primarily an index for the WAL file.
In WAL mode, multiple database connections sharing the same XXX.db file need 
to access and update this shared memory location to coordinate access to the 
WAL file.

The shared memory file does not contain persistent data and is only present 
while the database is actively in WAL mode.


In summary, these files indicate that your SQLite database, managed by 
SQLAlchemy, is utilizing WAL mode for enhanced performance and concurrency.

When you use DB Browser for SQLite to look at a database operating in
WAL mode, you will see the full, current state of the data, which includes
committed changes from the .db-wal file.
